@flexiarg collaboration-coherence/determined-fork-proto-psr
@title Determined Forks Get a Warrant, Not a Question
@sigils [⑂/⊢]
@keywords fork, warrant, proto-PSR, over-asking, operator attention, escalation, safe-default, autonomy, ChipWitz
@audience agents deciding whether to escalate a choice to the operator
@tone corrective
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a choice has a FINDABLE warrant — a standing contract, a documented preference, the method, or prior coaching — name the warrant (a proto-PSR) and proceed. Reserve operator escalations for GENUINELY undetermined forks (competing legitimate values, irreversible, operator-life-decision). Escalating a determined fork burns a round-trip and abdicates a judgement you are equipped to make.

  + context: You face a fork — which target, which approach, which option — and feel the pull to
    ask the operator rather than decide.

  + IF:
      You are about to escalate a choice to the operator (or, autonomous, to hold and wait).

  + HOWEVER:
      Most forks are *determined*: the warrant exists and is findable — the standing contract
      already prefers X; the doc names the next step; the method derives it; you were coached on it.
      Escalating a determined fork is over-asking: it costs an operator round-trip and signals you
      cannot make a judgement you can. (Over-asking is as much a discipline failure as over-reaching.)

  + THEN:
      Run the test: *is the warrant findable?* If YES → name it explicitly (a proto-PSR: "choosing
      X because the contract/doc/method/coaching says so") and proceed. If NO — genuinely
      undetermined: competing legitimate values, irreversible, or an operator-life-decision → escalate
      it; or, in an autonomous run, take the safe default (skip/hold) and QUEUE the question for
      review rather than block.

  + BECAUSE:
      The operator's attention is the scarce resource; spend it only where the choice is genuinely
      theirs. This is the inverse of trusting the method early (`[[feedback_trust_the_method_early]]`):
      don't *force* a direction prematurely, but don't *ask* when it is already determined. The
      warranted-work layer (`[[M-chipwitz-corps]]`) is the institutional form of this rule — supply
      the warrant and proceed.

  + canonical-instance:
      The WM-pilot cycle-5 A/B fork (full vs partial discharge) was put to the operator as a
      question, but the standing contract already preferred the measured-pair path — it should have
      been proto-PSR'd and flown. The over-ask became the ChipWitz lesson; the retrospective that
      first flattered it as "correct escalation" was itself caught by the review split. Distilled
      WM-pilot 2026-06-11.
